:INFO
Common Problems and Fixes
Most cast iron issues come down to too much oil, too little heat, or \
moisture. This page covers the most frequent problems and exactly how \
to correct them without starting the whole process over.

:PATH
Problem: Surface Is Sticky or Tacky
This means you applied too much oil before baking.
|
:INFO
Problem: Surface Is Sticky or Tacky
This means you applied too much oil before baking. The layer polymerized on the outside \
but stayed wet underneath. Bake the pan at 230 C for 45 minutes to try to cure it out, \
then scrub with steel wool and re-season with a much thinner wipe of oil.

:PATH
Problem: Food Still Sticks
Seasoning builds up over months of cooking, not after one or two sessions.
|
:INFO
Problem: Food Still Sticks
Seasoning builds up over months of cooking, not after one or two sessions. Stick to \
high-fat cooking (bacon, sausage, sauteed vegetables in butter) for the first several \
uses. Avoid acidic foods like tomato sauce and citrus early on as acid strips fresh

:PATH
Problem: Rust Came Back Fast
If rust returns within a few days of seasoning, two things may be happening.
|
:INFO
Problem: Rust Came Back Fast
If rust returns within a few days of seasoning, two things may be happening. Either the \
pan was not dried completely before oiling, or the seasoning layers are too thin and not \
yet protective. Scrub, dry over heat on the stove for 3 minutes, then oil and

:PATH
Problem: Black Flakes Coming Off
This is usually carbonized old seasoning or food residue, not rust.
|
:INFO
Problem: Black Flakes Coming Off
This is usually carbonized old seasoning or food residue, not rust. Strip the pan \
completely with steel wool, rinse and dry, then re-season from scratch. This is not a \
sign the pan is ruined. It is just overdue for a reset.

:CHECKLIST
Things to Avoid With Cast Iron
[ ] Soaking in water or leaving wet in the sink
[ ] Washing with dish soap regularly (occasional use is actually fine)
[ ] Cooking tomato sauce, wine reductions, or citrus in a new pan
[ ] Storing with the lid on when moisture could be trapped inside
[ ] Putting it in the dishwasher

:NOTE
When to Use the Oven vs the Stovetop
The oven gives even all-around heat and is best for initial seasoning and \
restores. Stovetop seasoning works for quick maintenance after cooking. \
For a full restore or new pan, always use the oven. It produces a harder, \
more durable layer than stovetop alone.
